<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="plant-fibres">Plant Fibres</h2><ul><li><p>Sclerenchyma fibres and xylem vessels are made of <b>long, hollow plant cells</b></p></li><li><p>These cells are hollow due to the fact that their cell contents <b>died</b> (often due to the lignification of the cell wall, which makes it almost impossible for substances to enter or leave the cell)</p></li><li><p>These fibres have <b>great strength</b>, which is a property that is often exploited by humans</p><ul><li><p>They are useful in making <b>rope</b> and certain <b>fabrics</b> are made from plant fibres (e.g. cotton and hemp)</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Their strength is due to certain factors affecting the cell wall:</p><ul><li><p>The <b>arrangement of microfibrils</b> in a mesh-like pattern</p></li><li><p><b>Secondary thickening</b>, which results in a thick secondary cell wall developing which often contains <b>lignin</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Cellulose_ Structure linking to function of cellulose" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1288" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Cellulose_-Structure-linking-to-function-of-cellulose.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-Structure-linking-to-function-of-cellulose.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-Structure-linking-to-function-of-cellulose.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-Structure-linking-to-function-of-cellulose.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.